    {
      "beat_id": "B01",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "This is Liam, in for Bear. Electrons diffract through crystals, and de Broglie's formula applies to people too. So why does a person walking through a doorway show no visible wave spreading?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "remotion",
        "motion": "hold",
        "remotion": {
          "pattern": "ClaudeComposerAsk",
          "provenance": "proven-core/ClaudeComposerAsk",
          "version": "1",
          "props": {
            "command": "Why doesn't a walking person visibly diffract through a doorway if every object has a de Broglie wavelength?",
            "topic": "QUANTUM MECHANICS — MATTER WAVES",
            "segment": "A Human Wavelength Too Small to See",
            "greeting": "Hallo, Liam",
            "runningText": "comparing wavelength with aperture…",
            "output": [
              "lambda = h/p applies at every mass.",
              "Human momentum makes lambda fantastically small."
            ],
            "folderLabel": "@NikBearBrown",
            "modelLabel": "Fable 5",
            "effortLabel": "High"
          },
          "rendered": {
            "out": "media/B01.mp4",
            "at": ""
          }
        }
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B01.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.99,
      "build": {
        "status": "VIDEO",
        "src": "media/B01.mp4",
        "filled_by": "media",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:06:26"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Diffraction becomes pronounced when an aperture or grating spacing is comparable to the wavelength. Electrons with atomic-scale wavelengths can therefore diffract from crystal planes.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.52,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B02.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:06:26"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "estimated_duration_s": 6,
      "narration_text": "What wavelength belongs to a walking human?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 3.14,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B03.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:06:26"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "The de Broglie relation is lambda equals h over p. For ordinary walking, momentum is mass times speed.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "derive"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 7.13,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B04.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:06:26"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "Use seventy kilograms and one meter per second. The momentum is seventy kilogram meters per second, giving lambda about 9.5 times ten to the minus 36 meters.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "calculate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.62,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B05.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:06:26"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "That is about twenty orders of magnitude smaller than a proton-sized length near ten to the minus 15 meters, and roughly twenty-six orders below an atomic-scale electron wavelength.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "scan"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.73,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B06.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:06:26"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "A doorway is about one meter wide. Its width exceeds the human wavelength by roughly thirty-five orders of magnitude.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 7.36,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B07.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:06:26"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "The characteristic diffraction angle scales like lambda over aperture width. For this doorway, that is around ten to the minus 35 radians: effectively zero for any conceivable measurement here.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "derive"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.54,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B08.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:06:26"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Making a narrower slit only helps when its width approaches the wavelength. A ten to the minus 35 meter controlled aperture for a human is not physically realizable.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "zoom"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.09,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B09.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:06:26"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Large molecules can diffract because their masses and velocities still allow picometer-scale wavelengths, and experiments can build nanometer gratings with exquisite coherence.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B10.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.52,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B10.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T16:06:26"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B11",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "For a warm, interacting person, environmental decoherence would also destroy usable path coherence almost instantly. But the wavelength mismatch already makes doorway diffraction hopeless.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "qualify"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B11.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.63,
      "build": {
